# Rust Doesn't Have a Garbage Collector

This is a common misconception worth addressing directly. **Rust has no garbage collector** — this is actually one of its defining features and primary design goals.

---

## How Rust Actually Manages Memory

Rust uses a **compile-time ownership system** to manage memory with zero runtime overhead.

### The Three Core Rules

```rust
// RULE 1: Every value has a single owner
let s = String::from("hello");  // s owns this string

// RULE 2: Ownership can be moved
let s2 = s;                     // ownership transfers to s2
// println!("{}", s);           // COMPILE ERROR: s is no longer valid

// RULE 3: When the owner goes out of scope, memory is freed
{
    let s3 = String::from("world");
}   // s3 dropped here automatically — no GC needed
```

### Borrowing (Using Without Taking Ownership)

```rust
fn calculate_length(s: &String) -> usize {  // & means "borrow"
    s.len()
}   // s is NOT dropped here — we don't own it

fn main() {
    let s = String::from("hello");
    let len = calculate_length(&s);  // lend s, keep ownership
    println!("{} has length {}", s, len);  // s still valid
}
```

### Mutable Borrowing Rules

```rust
let mut s = String::from("hello");

let r1 = &s;      // immutable borrow — OK
let r2 = &s;      // second immutable borrow — OK
// let r3 = &mut s; // COMPILE ERROR: can't mix mutable + immutable borrows

println!("{} {}", r1, r2);
// r1 and r2 no longer used after this point

let r3 = &mut s;  // NOW OK — previous borrows are done
r3.push_str(" world");
```

